# Tools

Workspace conventions (commit style, branch naming, etc.) are defined in `preferences.json` — edit that file to customize.

Each installed skill documents its own tools and commands inside its module (`skills/<name>/`) and is surfaced in `skills/INDEX.md`. This file keeps only the workspace-wide conventions every skill inherits.

## Public vs internal surfaces

**Critical rule.** There are two distinct surfaces. Never mix them.

| Surface | Scope | Allowed references |
|---|---|---|
| **Internal** — workspace files (MEMORY.md, task logs, designs, plans, agent prompts) | Private to this workspace | Anything. Task IDs, design IDs, sub-item codes, the agent's name, workspace paths |
| **External** — PR titles + bodies, commit messages, issue comments, chat messages, customer-facing docs | Public to your team / reviewers | Public ticket IDs, public PR refs, repo-relative file paths only |

**Banned in external surfaces (PRs, commits, chat, docs):**
- Internal task and design IDs
- Sub-item references (e.g. `A1`, `A2`)
- The agent's own workspace name
- Workspace paths (`plans/`, `designs/`, `agents/`, `tasks/`, `workspaces/`, or anything under the workspace root)

Before posting any external text, run a final scrub for those tokens and strip every match. The `scrub` skill is the mechanical gate for this — an installable registry module (`straper add scrub`) that fails on banned tokens deterministically. When describing follow-up work in a PR, describe it functionally ("custom attributes UI in a follow-up PR"), never by internal sub-item ID.

## Commits

Commit style and conventions are configured in `preferences.json` under the `commits` key.

- Follow the commit style defined in preferences (default: conventional commits)
- Only output the title and description, no affirmation or extra commentary
- No "Generated by [AI]" footer unless `commits.include_footer` is true
- No bold markdown (\*\*) in commit messages
- No `Co-authored-by` trailers unless `commits.include_co_authored_by` is true
- No internal references (see Public vs internal surfaces above)

If `commits.skip_hooks_env` is set in preferences (e.g., `SKIP_GIT_HOOKS=1`), use it when committing in worktrees where pre-commit hooks may not work in non-interactive shells.

Example:
```bash
git commit -m "$(cat <<'EOF'
feat: add new feature
EOF
)"
```

## Branch Naming

Branch format is configured in `preferences.json` under the `branches` key.

- `prefix` — prepended to all branch names (e.g., `yourname/`)
- `format` — pattern using `{prefix}` and `{name}` placeholders

Example with prefix `yourname/`: `yourname/fix-something`, `yourname/add-feature`. Keep branch names domain-named, not workflow-named — they are visible to your team, so no internal sub-item suffixes.

## Subagents

{{agent_display_name}} is the orchestrator. {{user_name}} talks and plans with {{agent_display_name}}. {{agent_display_name}} spawns subagents to do the work.

### Rules

- Use up to `subagents.max_parallel_read` (default: 5) parallel subagents for read-only operations (research, review, exploration)
- Use only `subagents.max_parallel_write` (default: 1) subagent at a time for build/test operations (to avoid resource contention)
- Each subagent gets a clear, scoped task and bounded set of files
- Subagents work in `workspaces/` worktrees, never in {{user_name}}'s external repos

### Subagent Checklist

Before any subagent does work in a repo, it MUST read that repo's `AGENTS.md` if present, otherwise `CLAUDE.md`. This is the single authoritative rule — it applies to all subagents, every time.

When spawning subagents, always include this instruction:

> Read the repo's `AGENTS.md` or `CLAUDE.md` before starting any work.

> Keep comments minimal: one line max, only for a constraint the code can't express on its own. When a task involves several sequential steps, do NOT put an explanatory comment above each one — that is individually defensible but collectively a wall of prose.

### Worker Commits

Workers MUST commit their own changes at the end of each dispatch — a conventional commit scoped to that dispatch (`git commit -- <paths>`), using the preferences skip-hooks env in worktrees. Do NOT push — {{user_name}} pushes after review.

This creates a clean "worker output" commit. When {{user_name}} layers tweaks on top, his changes show up as a separate diff against the worker's commit instead of being mixed into one end-of-task commit. It is how worker quality gets audited. Include this step explicitly in every worker prompt — the commit is part of "done", not a follow-up.

When multiple workers edit the workspace root itself, only one COMMITTING worker runs at a time — the shared git index races across parallel commits. Read-only fan-out is unrestricted.

### Minimal Comment Density

Code shipped under {{user_name}}'s name must have LOW comment density: a comment exists only to state a constraint the code cannot express (an API fact, a non-obvious trap). No JSDoc walls, no narrating machine behavior, no rationale essays — the code and its tests document behavior. Watch the aggregate trap: justified-in-isolation comments above every sequential step still add up to noise. Cap it explicitly in worker prompts. This applies to code in external repos AND to scripts, skills, and hooks in this workspace.

### Orchestration Pipeline

Standard phases {{agent_display_name}} follows for task execution:

| Phase | Agents | Concurrency | Trigger |
|-------|--------|-------------|---------|
| Discovery | Explore (up to 5) | Parallel | Task moves to `in_progress` |
| Implementation | general-purpose (1) | Sequential | Plan approved |
| Verification | `scripts/verify.sh` | Sequential (1) | Implementation complete |
| Pre-PR Review | code-reviewer + domain agents | Parallel (up to 5) | Verification passed |
| PR Preparation | pr-preparer or technical-writer | Sequential | Review passed |
| Post-Merge | Cleanup (worktrees, task status) | Sequential | PR merged |

Reviewer and writer profiles live in `agents/` — adapt them to your project.

### Patterns

Research/Exploration (parallel, up to 5):

- Map out a codebase area
- Read and summarize changes across repos
- Check for patterns, conventions, or prior art

Code Review (parallel, up to 5):

- One agent per repo or area (backend, frontend, docs, tests)
- Each reports findings, {{agent_display_name}} synthesizes

Build/Test (sequential, 1 at a time):

- Run tests, builds, or any resource-intensive operation
- Wait for completion before spawning the next

## Plans

- Plans always go to `plans/` directory
- Naming: `{topic}.md` (e.g., `system-overhaul.md`, `auth-flow-plan.md`)
- Include date, status (draft/approved/done), and context section
